  • <internal>
  • AllSystemCSSProperties

Interface AllSystemCSSProperties

Map of all available CSS properties (including aliases) and their raw value. Only used internally to map CSS properties to input types (responsive value, theme function or nested) in SystemCssProperties.

Hierarchy

  • Omit<StandardCSSProperties, keyof OverwriteCSSProperties>
  • OverwriteCSSProperties
  • AliasesCSSProperties
    • AllSystemCSSProperties

Optional KhtmlBoxAlign

KhtmlBoxAlign?: BoxAlign | BoxAlign[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxAlign

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:7984

The box-align CSS property specifies how an element aligns its contents across its layout in a perpendicular direction. The effect of the property is only visible if there is extra space in the box.

Syntax: start | center | end | baseline | stretch

Initial value: stretch

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxDirection

KhtmlBoxDirection?: BoxDirection | BoxDirection[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxDirection

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:7994

The box-direction CSS property specifies whether a box lays out its contents normally (from the top or left edge), or in reverse (from the bottom or right edge).

Syntax: normal | reverse | inherit

Initial value: normal

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxFlex

KhtmlBoxFlex?: BoxFlex | BoxFlex[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxFlex

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8004

The -moz-box-flex and -webkit-box-flex CSS properties specify how a -moz-box or -webkit-box grows to fill the box that contains it, in the direction of the containing box's layout.

Syntax: <number>

Initial value: 0

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxFlexGroup

KhtmlBoxFlexGroup?: BoxFlexGroup | BoxFlexGroup[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxFlexGroup

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8014

The box-flex-group CSS property assigns the flexbox's child elements to a flex group.

Syntax: <integer>

Initial value: 1

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxLines

KhtmlBoxLines?: BoxLines | BoxLines[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxLines

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8024

The box-lines CSS property determines whether the box may have a single or multiple lines (rows for horizontally oriented boxes, columns for vertically oriented boxes).

Syntax: single | multiple

Initial value: single

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxOrdinalGroup

KhtmlBoxOrdinalGroup?: BoxOrdinalGroup | BoxOrdinalGroup[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxOrdinalGroup

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8034

The box-ordinal-group CSS property assigns the flexbox's child elements to an ordinal group.

Syntax: <integer>

Initial value: 1

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxOrient

KhtmlBoxOrient?: BoxOrient | BoxOrient[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxOrient

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8044

This is a property of the original CSS Flexible Box Layout Module draft, and has been replaced by a newer standard. See flexbox for information about the current standard.

Syntax: horizontal | vertical | inline-axis | block-axis | inherit

Initial value: inline-axis (horizontal in XUL)

deprecated

Optional KhtmlBoxPack

KhtmlBoxPack?: BoxPack | BoxPack[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlBoxPack

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8054

The -moz-box-pack and -webkit-box-pack CSS properties specify how a -moz-box or -webkit-box packs its contents in the direction of its layout. The effect of this is only visible if there is extra space in the box.

Syntax: start | center | end | justify

Initial value: start

deprecated

Optional KhtmlLineBreak

KhtmlLineBreak?: LineBreak | LineBreak[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlLineBreak

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8064

The line-break CSS property sets how to break lines of Chinese, Japanese, or Korean (CJK) text when working with punctuation and symbols.

Syntax: auto | loose | normal | strict | anywhere

Initial value: auto

deprecated

Optional KhtmlOpacity

KhtmlOpacity?: Opacity | Opacity[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlOpacity

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8074

The opacity CSS property sets the opacity of an element. Opacity is the degree to which content behind an element is hidden, and is the opposite of transparency.

Syntax: <alpha-value>

Initial value: 1.0

deprecated

Optional KhtmlUserSelect

KhtmlUserSelect?: UserSelect | UserSelect[]

Inherited from Omit.KhtmlUserSelect

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:8084

The **user-select** CSS property controls whether the user can select text. This doesn't have any effect on content loaded as chrome, except in textboxes.

Syntax: auto | text | none | contain | all

Initial value: auto

deprecated

Optional MozAnimation

MozAnimation?: <internal>.Animation<string & {}> | <internal>.Animation<string & {}>[]

Inherited from Omit.MozAnimation

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:7547

The animation shorthand CSS property applies an animation between styles. It is a shorthand for animation-name, animation-duration, animation-timing-function, animation-delay, animation-iteration-count, animation-direction, animation-fill-mode, and animation-play-state.

Syntax: <single-animation>#

Optional MozAnimationDelay

MozAnimationDelay?: AnimationDelay<string & {}> | AnimationDelay<string & {}>[]

Inherited from Omit.MozAnimationDelay

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:5746

The animation-delay CSS property specifies the amount of time to wait from applying the animation to an element before beginning to perform the animation. The animation can start later, immediately from its beginning, or immediately and partway through the animation.

Syntax: <time>#

Initial value: 0s

Optional MozAnimationDirection

Syntax: <single-animation-direction>#

Initial value: normal

The -moz-appearance and -webkit-appearance properties are non-standard versions of this property, used (respectively) by Gecko (Firefox) and by WebKit-based (e.g., Safari) and Blink-based (e.g., Chrome, Opera) browsers to achieve the same thing. Optional appearance

appearance?: Appearance | Appearance[]

Inherited from Omit.appearance

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:261

The **appearance** CSS property is used to display an element using platform-native styling, based on the operating system's theme. The -moz-appearance and -webkit-appearance properties are non-standard versions of this property, used (respectively) by Gecko (Firefox) and by WebKit-based (e.g., Safari) and Blink-based (e.g., Chrome, Opera) browsers to achieve the same thing. Note that Firefox and Edge also support -webkit-appearance, for compatibility reasons.

Syntax: none | auto | textfield | menulist-button | <compat-auto>

Initial value: auto

Chrome Firefox Safari Edge IE
84 80 3 -x- 84 No
1 -x- 1 -x- 12 -x-
see

https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/CSS/appearance

Optional azimuth

azimuth?: Azimuth | Azimuth[]

Inherited from Omit.azimuth

  • Defined in node_modules/csstype/index.d.ts:7706

In combination with elevation, the azimuth CSS property enables different audio sources to be positioned spatially for aural presentation. This is important in that it provides a natural way to tell several voices apart, as each can be positioned to originate at a different location on the sound stage. Stereo output produce a lateral sound stage, while binaural headphones and multi-speaker setups allow for a fully three-dimensional stage.

Syntax: <angle> | [ [ left-side | far-left | left | center-left | center | center-right | right | far-right | right-side ] || behind ] | leftwards | rightwards

Initial value: center

deprecated

The **max-block-size** CSS property specifies the maximum size of an element in the direction opposite that of the writing direction as specified by writing-mode.
